Accounting and Business Research, 2013 Vol. 
43, No. 5, 483–505, http://dx.doi.org/10.1080/00014788.2013.798581 Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 and encompass tangibles, intangibles, services and intellectual capital. They evoke a spectrum of conceptual views from facilitating in ternational trade through to enabling tax evasion and creating social injustice (Matsui 2011). 
Recent estimates suggest intra-group transactions account for 60% of world trade (OECD 2008); the exports of multinational enterprises and their afﬁliates comprise one-third of the global total (UNCTAD 2010) and the periodic Ernst & Young surveys (2011) indicate multinational enterprise executives regard tra nsfer pricing as their most important tax issue. 
In contrast, the accounting audience appears largely uninformed on this key area of accounting practice and seemingly little attention is paid by the media, politicians, regulators, corporate critics and standard setters (Sikka and Willmott 2010). 
Furthermore, the Financial Accounting Standards Board Interpretation No. 48 (FIN 48), requiring taxpayers to report in the annual accounts any uncertain tax positions, represents a recent and rare exception to the la ck of comprehensive disclosure requirements by generally accepted accounting principles internationally (Borkowski and Gaffney 2012). 
Transfer pricing manipulation theory posits that multinational enterprises have incentives to over- or under-invoice their intra-group transfers in the presence of corporate income tax differentials between host and home country (Lin et al. 1993, Eden 1998). 
Speciﬁcally, afﬁliates operating in a high-tax country are expected to show lower proﬁtability than domestic companies due to either artiﬁcially deﬂated taxable revenues or inﬂated deductible expenses relating to intragroup trade. 
Several methods are proposed to verify transfer pricing compliance (see the OECD (2010a, 2010b) and UN (2011) model conventions). 
The search for a set of comparable companies under these methods becomes essential for the detection of manipulations in intra-group transactions in multinational corporations and this is particularly true when the comparable proﬁts or the transactional net margin methods are employed. 
Here, the focus to verify transfer pricing compliance moves from individual transactions to the proﬁts of comparable companies. 
The careful selection of comparable companies is vital to demonstrate that any differences in profitability between a tested party and unrelated parties are realistically attributable to transfer prices not in line with the arm’s length proﬁt principle. 
This procedure poses particular challenges since price is only one component of proﬁt. 
Independent taxpayers undertaking similar activities and functions may exhibit different cost structures and systems, operate in different geographic locations or markets, the quality of management may differ as well as capital costs, corporate objectives, business efﬁciency and experience. 
The purpose of this study is to test whether the use of comparable proﬁt-based methods can reliably detect international transfer pricing manipulation in an institutional setting where a high corporate tax rate is linked with a business environment where afﬁliates of multinational enterprises are expected to display strong comparative advantages relative to domestic companies. 
Concerns on the implications of the transfer pricing manipulation theory, and the assumption that where assets are located should reﬂect the expected return (Wheeler 1988, 1990), motivated numerous empirical studies which compare foreign-controlled companies (FCCs) and domesticcontrolled companies (DCCs) proﬁtability to demonstrate that opportunistic income-shifting activities were in place (Wheeler 1988, Kim and Lyn 1990, Grubert and Mutti 1991, Harris et al. 1991, Grubert et al. 1993, Crain and Stitts 1994, Collins et al. 1997, Grubert 1997, Collins et al. 1998). 
Early contributions based on the USA correlate differences in proﬁtability with differentials in corporate tax rates and import tariffs to infer that aggressive transfer pricing is the cause of DCCs outperforming FCCs. 
Similar arguments characterise a few empirical studies that collect evidence on Europe by focusing on the UK, Norway and Germany (Oyelere and Emmanuel 1998, Langli and Saudagaran 2004, Weichenrieder 2009). 
484 A. Mura et al. Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 The interpretation of these ﬁnding s as an indication of the presence of international transfer pricing anomalies in multinational afﬁliates rests on internalisation theory, a long-established explanation of the existence and growth of multinational enterprises (Dunning 1958, Caves 1996). 
In order to engage in successful foreign direct investments, multinational enterprises should have superior technological, managerial or other intangible advantages over domestic ﬁrms. 
In the long term, their subsidiaries beneﬁt from these comparative advantages after familiarisation with the host countries’ culture, business practices and customer preferences in the start-up period. 
Accordingly, lower levels of proﬁtability in FCCs than in DCCs contradict the importance of comparative advantage underpinning an international strategy and provides evidence to support the anomaly as in the international transfer pricing studies. 
The possible interaction between the comparative advantages and international transfer pricing manipulation incentives may explain why the literature focusing on comparative advantage theory offers mixed results on the expected superiority of FCCs (Globerman et al. 1994, Doms and Jensen 1998, Girma et al. 2001, Harris 2002, Harris and Robinson 2003, Benfratello and Sembenelli 2006). 
In this study we suggest that the interaction between the incentives to undertake international transfer pricing manipulations and the comparative advantage enjoyed by the FCCs might produce a less clear-cut picture than that postulated by the transfer pricing manipulation theory and may, then, undermine the ability of comparability methods to detect transfer pricing manipulations. 
We undertake a proﬁt-comparability analysis to detect the presence of international transfer pricing manipulations at the ﬁrm level. 
Essentially, the purpose is to empirically investigate the ﬁscal implications of using independent domestic companies as comparables to judge the congruence of FCCs proﬁtability in one European jurisdiction. 
To this end, we focus on a sample of Italian companies. 
The choice of Italy is motivated by the peculiarities of the Italian institutional framework which is markedly different from those characterising other countries analysed in previous international transfer pricing studies. 
In particular, Italy shows the two characteristics that may generate conﬂicting predictions between the transfer pricing manipulation theory and the internalisation theory: (i) a high level of corporate taxation; (ii) a low level of foreign direct investment attractiveness. 
In spite of various ﬁscal reforms, Italy remains characterised by high statutory corporate tax rates and high effective corporate tax rates as compared to the majority of other countries (Nicode`me 2007). 
This is conﬁrmed by the Global Competitiveness Report (World Economic Forum 2012): out of 144 countries Italy ranks 141st on the extent and effect of tax and 133rd in terms of total tax rate. 
In this respect, the tax incentives for multinational enterprises with afﬁliates in Italy to shift income to countries with lower corporate tax rates may be particularly pronounced. 
The Global Competitiveness Report also provides a ranking on the extent to which rules governing foreign direct investment actually encourage investment (business impact of rules on foreign direct investment) where Italy is ranked 126th. 
1 Furthermore, statistical analyses conﬁrm that Italy is signiﬁcan tly less able than other European Union countries of similar size to attract foreign direct investments (Italian Institute for Foreign Trade 2010). 
This implies that FCCs operating in Italy are expected to exhibit strong comparative advantages to counterbalance the risk proﬁle of their investments. 
Overall, these institutional features are suitable for empirically observing how internalisation and transfer pricing manipulation theories display their potentially contrasti ng effects on FCCs’ proﬁtability and for investigating whether the reliability of comparability analysis might remain an attainable goal under such circumstances. 
The results of an extensive set of univariate and multivariate tests, conducted on a sample consisting of 416,248 ﬁrm-year observations of independent Italian companies and of 17,189 ﬁrmyear observations of FCCs for the period 1998 –2010, show that FCCs generally outperform DCCs. 
This ﬁnding is in stark contrast to other international transfer pricing empirical studies Accounting and Business Research 485 Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 but consistent with the presence of comparative advantages in foreign afﬁliates and holds after including several control variables and alternative proﬁt-level indicators in the multivariate tests. 
Next, as the transfer pricing Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) guidelines suggest that the use of interquartile range might help to enhance the reliability of the comparability analysis (OECD 2010a, 2010b, par. 
3.57), we also analyse how FCCs’ performances relate to the interquartile range of the DCCs’ return on assets (ROA) distribution. 
The ﬁndings show that more than 70% of FCCs report values of ROA falling either above the 75 percentile or within the interquartile range. 
In other words, only a low percentage of FCCs operating in Italy would be subject to ﬁscal enquiries under the suspicion of transfer pricing manipulation. 
Overall, our analysis offers strong support for the presence of comparative advantages in FCCs as postulated by internalisation theory and shows a potential room for an unimpeded use of transfer pricing manipulation. 
This is because a legitimate high proﬁtab ility due to comparative advantages may represent a comfortable buffer that unfairly protects FCCs from ﬁscal authorities in their income-shifting activities and the use of the interquartile range as an assessment method does not seem to remove this concern. 
The remainder of the paper contains ﬁve sections, the ﬁrst of which explains the peculiarities of proﬁt-based methods to monitor international transfer pricing behaviour. 
Section 3 reports the theoretical development of the two alternative hypotheses to be tested. 
The research design is explained in Section 4. The results of the empirical tests are then given in Section 5 and Section 6 discusses the policy implications of the study. 
2. Proﬁt-based methods and comparability in international transfer pricing Proﬁt-based methods, such as the comparable proﬁts and the transactional net margin methods, use average industry rates of return on proﬁt to value the taxpayers’ proﬁts adherence to the arm’s length principle (Eden 1998, p. 420). 
Both methods apply the “arm’s length” principle through the examination of proﬁts – instead of focusing on prices – that arise from particular transactions or activities (Culbertson 1995). 
The procedure involves testing one of the transacting enterprises’ proﬁt-level indicators (such as ROA or operating proﬁt to costs or sales) with those earned by unrelated enterprises (OECD 2010a, 2010b, par. 
2.58; Income Tax Regulation, Section 1.482– 5). When the tested enterprise’s ﬁnancial results fall outside the comparable arm’s length range, a ﬁscal enquiry leading to a possible audit is triggered. 
2 The search for comparable companies plays the heroic role of guaranteeing that they enjoy market positions, levels of efﬁciency, advanced technology and so on that are similar to those of the tested party in order to realistically infer that eventual differences in proﬁts relate to abuse in transfer pricing (Emmanuel and Mehafdi 1994). 
In making the comparison between intra-group and unrelated party transactions not only the internalisation concept but also value chain, market versus hierarchy, strategic management and multinational enterprises as strategi c oligopolists considerations may be taken into account (Eden 1998). 
The different acceptable methods can yield different proﬁts for subsidiaries or afﬁliates “since no method is suitable in every possible situation” (OECD 1994, par. 
84). 
The previous recommendation of the OECD favoured the exercise of good judgement, selecting a method and transfer price that best ﬁts the facts and circumstances of the case. 
However, since the current advice is to choose the most reliable transfer pricing method (OECD 2010a, 2010b), the transactional net margin method is no longer a method of last resort. 
Reliability therefore occupies a fulcrum position in policing transfer pricing manipulation, simultaneously enabling international trade and development. 
3 As regards Italy, statutory rules require transfer prices to be set at normal value (art. 
110, par. 
7 of the Italian Income Tax Code), whose deﬁnition substantially coincides with the OECD arm’s length principle. 
The International Standard Ruling Report issued by the Italian ﬁscal authority 486 A. Mura et al. Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 has ofﬁcially recognised, for interpretative purposes, the 1995 version of the OECD guidelines (Agenzia delle Entrate 2010, par. 
4). This document also recognises that over the period 2004– 2009 the transactional net margin method was by far the most popular transfer pricing method in advanced pricing agreements: it was applied in 53% of the cases. 
3. Hypotheses development The transfer price manipulation theory (Eden 1998), regardless of the level of taxation or the degree of attractiveness for foreign direct investment in the host country, requires transfer prices in line with the arm’s length standard. 
When FCCs equalise the performance of independent comparable companies, this theory recognises the transfer pricing practices of these companies as congruent with the arm’s length principle. 
By contrast, the presence of signiﬁcant differences in ﬁnancial performance between FCCs and DCCs is normally interpreted as offering an indirect evidence of potential transfer pricing abuse: it is a manifestation of income-shifting strategies for tax-minimisation purposes (Emma nuel and Oyelere 2002, p. 4). This is because, according to the transfer price manipulation theory, a multinational company is expected to over-state intra-group exports and under-state intra-ﬁrm imports in order to minimise its global tax liability when the host country presents a level of taxation higher than the parent company (Lin et al. 1993). 
Therefore, foreign subsidiaries will report, ceteris paribus, a lower proﬁt than domestic companies due to net effect of either maximising tax deductible expenses or minimising tax revenues through the alteration of transfer prices. 
Obviously, the incentives for an FCC to engage in income-shifting strategies are expected to be especially pronounced in an institutional context where corporate taxation is strongly penalising in the host country as is the case of Italy. 
In sum, under the transfer price manipulation theory we formulate the following hypothesis: H 1 : Foreign controlled companies report signiﬁcantly lower proﬁtability than domestic independent companies operating in Italy as they undertake international transfer pricing manipulations. 
Empirical evidence which supports this hypothesis would imply that FCCs are artiﬁcially manipulating transfer prices to shift proﬁts outside Italy as postulated by transfer pricing manipulation theory. 
As a consequence, proﬁt-based comparability methods will be able to detect international transfer pricing manipulation to the extent they materialise in terms of differences in proﬁtability between FCCs and DCCs. 
However, we suggest that in a higher-taxed host country, as is the case of Italy, foreign afﬁliates may still present higher proﬁtability levels than domestic companies due to the presence of substantial comparative advantages (Buckley and Casson 2009). 
Thus, proﬁt-based comparability methods will not provide a signal to ﬁscal authorities on the presence of abuse in international transfer pricing practices. 
We postulate the following alternative hypothesis: H 2 : Foreign controlled companies report signiﬁcantly higher proﬁtability than domestic independent companies operating in Italy due to their comparative advantages. 
Empirical evidence that supports this second hypothesis will open to question the reliability of the comparison with no negative ﬁscal implications for these companies. 
A higher proﬁt, though not in line with comparable companies, will be accepted by the local ﬁscal authorities as it generates higher tax revenues for the host country. 
In sum, under proﬁt-based methods these companies have scope for manipulating international transfer pricing without facing ﬁscal consequences Accounting and Business Research 487 Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 because their performance remains higher than that of DCCs. 
Therefore, the extent to which domestic companies show a very low degree of proﬁtability, due to the lack of competitiveness and/or to a high degree of tax evasion, perversely increases the scope for transfer pricing manipulation by foreign afﬁliates without arousing the attention of the ﬁscal authority. 
4. Sample, variable construction and statistical tests 4.1 The sampling process The sample of DCCs and FCCs was drawn from the database AIDA, managed by Bureau van Dijk, which contains detailed ﬁnancial accounting and ownership data on a large number of companies located in Italy. 
In order to ensure that the sample properly represents the Italian productive sector, and since AIDA has substantially increased the amount of available information only from the late 1990s, the sampling process has focused on the period spanning 1998– 2010. 
The substantial number of Italian companies captured in th e database and the introduction of proﬁt-based transfer pricing methods prompted the selection of this time period. 
In effect, the comparable proﬁts method was ﬁrst introduced in the USA in 1992, and a few years later the OECD ofﬁcially introduced the transactional net margin method as did the UN, with a similar set of rules to those of the comparable proﬁts method (Culbertson 1995). 
The ﬁnal sample is the result of the application of several selection criteria. 
First, due to their speciﬁcities in terms of business policies and strategies, the sample does not include ﬁnancial, real estate ﬁrms and ﬁ r ms with act i vities related t o the public sector. 
Second, coopera tive ﬁrms as non-proﬁt-maximising enti ties are also excluded from th e samp le that, therefore, consists of only limited liability corporations. 
Third, we require that all companies close their ﬁscal year at the end of the calendar year . 
Fourth, with the purpose of both eliminating concerns over the reliability of the accounting items provided at the ﬁrm level and excluding unimportant ﬁrms in ﬁnancial terms, we maintain in the sample only ﬁrms with a positive book-equity value (as in Klassen et al. 1993) and with a minimum value of total sales equal to E1,000,000. 
Fi fth, we maintain in the sample only ﬁrms for which we can clearly identify the nationality of the owner from the database. 
Finally, we remove f rom the s ample DCCs th at are not independent entities as they are c ontrolled by another corporation that holds at least 50% of the total ownership. 
Applying these criteria allows our selection process to conform to the approach adopted by ﬁscal authorities in identifying comparables when the purpose is to detect international transfer pricing manipulation practices. 
The ﬁnal sample refers to 39,901 unique ﬁrms with each ﬁrm entering the database on average for 10.6 years. 
As shown by Panel A of Table 1, 416,248 ﬁrm-year observations relate to DCCs and 17,189 to FCCs. 
The number of observations achieves the maximum value of 37,296 (1532) for DCCs (FCCs) in 2006 (2004). 
Panel B of Table 1 shows the sample distribution across three sectors (manufacturing, commercial and other services) identiﬁed on the basis of the economic activities (ATECO) classiﬁcation provided by the Italian National Institute of Statistics. 
4 From this distribution, we observe that the largest number of ﬁrms is concentrated in the manufacturing sector: around 54% of the DCCs and 46% of the FCCs. 
4.2 The performance measure The ROA is the measure of ﬁrm proﬁtability computed as the ratio of net operating proﬁt (the difference between operating revenues (O_REV ) and costs (O_COSTS) as identiﬁed by the Italian civil code 5 ) and the value of total assets (ASSETS), net of the amount of liquidity (LIQUIDITY), obtained from the ﬁrm balance sheet at the end of the ﬁnancial year. 
More 488 A. Mura et al. Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 formally, the ROA for company i at time t is deﬁned as follows: ROA i,t = O REV i,t − O COSTS i,t ASSETS i,t − LIQUIDITY i,t (1) Our choice to focus on the ROA as a measure of ﬁrm proﬁtability is motivated by two main reasons. 
First, this measure of performance has been widely employed in previous empirical studies on transfer pricing practices at the ﬁrm level (Wheeler 1988, Craven and Shearon 1996, Oyelere and Emmanuel 1998, Emmanuel and Oyelere 2002, Weichenrieder 2009). 
By employing this measure, we have the opportunity of a direct comparison of our results with other empirical studies. 
Second, the ROA is a proﬁt-level indicator commonly employed by both the UN and OECD transfer pricing regulations to apply the transactional net margin method and by the USA when using the comparable proﬁt method. 
Nonetheless, in order to verify the robustness of the results we replicate our statistical tests using alternative proﬁt-level indicators as dependent variables. 
In particular we use the ratio of “taxable income” to either total assets and equity as in Grubert et al. (1993) and Langli and Saudagaran (2004). 
Furthermore, in accordance with the OECD guidelines we carry out additional tests with two alternative measures: the return on costs (ROC) computed as the ratio of net operating proﬁt and total costs of production and the return on sales (ROS) whose denominator is total sales. 
4.3 Statistical tests The analysis of the differences between FCCs’ and DCCs’ performance consists of two steps. 
First, we test the hypothesis of the equality in median performances for the two groups of Table 1. Sample distribution. 
