. 
Accounting and Business Research 489 Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 observations by using the Wilcoxon rank-sum test, also known as the Mann2Whitney twosample statistic. 
Notably, as a non-parametric test, the Wilcoxon rank-sum test is less sensitive to the presence of extreme values in the ROA distribution than the two-sample t -test. Furthermore, it is valid for data from any type of distribution, whether normal or not. 
Second, we extend the analysis to a multivariate setting where ﬁrm performance (ROA) is expressed as a function of a set of covariates including company ownership. 
This further analysis is necessary as the univariate tests may reﬂect the presence of other factors other than simply being the consequence of the ownership variable. 
For instance, as suggested by Kim and Lyn (1990) and Langli and Saudagaran (2004), different values of ﬁnancial leverage, used as a proxy of ﬁnancial risk, may generate differences in proﬁtability. 
In a similar vein, the reliability of the comparison under the ROA depends on the extent to which the assets composition is similar among the ﬁrms included in the sample. 
In fact differences in performance may be related to differences in the asset structure (Langli and Saudagaran 2004) expressed by the ratio between ﬁxed assets and total assets: ﬁrms invest in ﬁxed assets when the expected net present value of the investment is positive. 
Thus, ﬁrms with a high level of ﬁxed assets to total assets ratio may have better investment opportunities than ﬁrms with lower ﬁxed assets to assets ratios, implying a positive effect on performance. 
However, this ratio may also impact on income via differences in costs due to depreciation. 
6 Start-up and maturation effects may also affect proﬁtability as ﬁrms move through the various stages of the business cycle. 
We control for this potential effect by introducing in the regression model the logarithmic transformation of the age of the ﬁrm measured in years. 
Finally, in the case of Italy, it is widely recognised that regional location plays a signiﬁcant role in determining the degree of proﬁtability at the ﬁrm level, providing some competitive advantages for companies located in the north, due to the business environment and availability of infrastructure (Leonardi 1995). 
Thus, the multivariate analysis is conducted by estimating the following linear regression model: ROA i,t =a+b 1 OWNER i +b 2 SIZE i,t +b 3 NORTH i +b 4 EQUITY i,t +b 5 FIXED i,t +b 6 AGE + YEAR + SECTOR + 1 i,t , (2) where ROA i,t is the return on assets of company i at time t, OWNER i is a dummy equal to 1 if the company i is controlled by a foreign owner and 0 otherwise, SIZE i,t is the log of total assets of company i at time t, NORTH i is a dummy equal to 1 if the company i is located in the north and 0 otherwise, EQUITY i,t is the ratio between equity and total assets for company i at time t, FIXED i,t is the ratio between tangible ﬁxed assets and total assets, AGE i,t is the log of the ﬁrm age in number of years that controls for the inﬂuence of maturation effects, YEAR is a vector of time dummies that controls for the inﬂuence of the business cycle on performance and SECTOR is a vector of dummies that controls for sector differences. 
The model is estimated using a median regression so as to replicate in a multivariate framework the non-parametric approach adopted in the univariate tests. 
More precisely, median regressions belong to the family of quantile regressions that aim to estimate the quantiles (in our case the median) of the conditional distribution of the response variable (ROA) as functions of the observed covariates. 
Koenker and Hallock (2001) show that quantile regression is equivalent to minimising a sum of asymmetrically weighted absolute residuals by means of a linear programming method. 
While the estimation method mirrors our univariate approach, to ease the comparison with previous studies, we also report the results using the more conventional ordinary least squares (OLS) estimator. 
Table 2 reports descriptive statistics for the full sample and separately for the group of DCCs and FCCs, for the ROA performance indicator and for the set of variables used in the multivariate 490 A. Mura et al. Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 tests. 
Panels B and C report the statistics separately for the two groups and clearly highlight the need to control for several differences between FCCs and DCCs: foreign companies are larger, are better capitalised, have a higher level of tangible ﬁxed assets to total assets ratio and tend to be more concentrated in the north of Italy. 
While some of these differences are likely to vanish if the comparison is made between groups that are homogenous in terms of size and sector, the multivariate tests represent an essential tool to remove the inﬂuence of any of these characteristics before formulating conclusions on the impact of the ownership structure on ROA. 
Therefore, the intention of including these control variables is to deﬁne more precisely the comparable range in order that reliable benchmarks are recognised. 
5. Empirical results 5.1 Univariate analysis This section discusses the results of the Wilcoxon rank-sum tests on the equality in performances that we have measured in terms of ROA between the sample of FCCs and the sample of DCCs operating in Italy. 
To compare the median performances realised by the two groups of companies, we start by eliminating the inﬂuence of the size differential on the performance levels. 
As anticipated in Section 4.3, FCCs are on average substantially larger than their Italian counterparts; therefore, Table 2. Descriptive statistics. 
