Accounting and Business Research 491 Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 any comparison in terms of performance conducted without controlling for this size differential may produce unreliable evidence. 
We control for the size effect by adopting a matching strategy. 
More precisely, we initially classiﬁed the FCCs into ﬁve size classes, based on the distribution of the (average) total assets over the sample period. 
7 Next, we have identiﬁed domestic ﬁrms that fall in each class on the basis of their average value of total assets. 
The domestic ﬁrms included in each size class of FCCs show an average value of total assets over the sample period between the minimum and the maximum (average) size value in that class. 
Table 3 reports the results of the univariate tests on the equality in median performances for each size class. 
The results of these tests do not appear supportive of our ﬁrst hypothesis discussed in Section 3. In particular, these tests do not conﬁrm the evidence provided by the prior literature showing that FCCs tend to underperform DCCs. 
By contrast, in our sample, in all size classes, the (median) performa nces of FCCs are signiﬁcantly higher than that of their independent domestic counterparts. 
This difference is, however, less pronounced among the largest ﬁrms. 
One possible interpretation for this result is that large FCCs when engaged in ﬁscal planning are more effective than small and medium FCCs in matching the proﬁtability of their DCC counterparts. 
Alternatively, we might speculate that small and medium DCCs have a strong tax avoidance attitude or a low level of competitiveness such that a compatible low proﬁtability for a multinational enterprise afﬁliate may trigger ﬁscal interest at the host and home jurisdictions. 
As differences in performance may also be related to business characteristics, in Table 4, we extend the analysis by repeating the Wilcoxon rank-sum test separately for different industry sectors. 
The sample is divided into three groups consisting of, respectively, manufacturing ﬁrms, ﬁrms operating in the commercial sector and ﬁrms offering non-ﬁnancial services. 
Overall, the results of these tests continue to conﬁrm the general ﬁnding emerging from Table 3, although some variations across sectors are clearly visible. 
Only in the third sub-sample, consisting of companies operating in the service sector, do FCCs outperform DCCs in all size classes, Table 3. Univariate tests by size class. 
