The univariate analysis shows that there are signiﬁcant differences in the median performances between DCCs and FCCs: in our sample FCCs perform relat ively better than DCCs, in particular in the case of small 2 medium enterprises and in the group of companies that offer nonﬁnancial services. 
These result s, therefore, are in sharp contrast with those found in previous studies that have employed an indirect method to detect the presence of international transfer pricing manipulation practices in FCCs and infer evidence of income-shifting mechanisms in multinational corporations (see, for example, Collins et al. 1997, 1998, Oyelere and Emmanuel 1998, Emmanuel and Oyelere 2002, Langli and Saudagaran 2004). 
Our ﬁndings are instead supportive of the presence of strong comparative advantages in FCCs as postulated by Hypothesis 2 that might undermine the ability of proﬁt comparable methods to detect international transfer pricing manipulations at the ﬁrm level. 
5.2 Regression analysis This section extends the analysis to a multiva riate setting by modelling the ROA as a function of a set of covariates including ﬁrm ownership. 
Table 5 shows the results of the median and OLS regression models estimated for each size class and with the full set of control variables. 
The evidence offered by these multivariate tests is broadly in line with the results of the univariate analysis reported in Table 3: FCCs outperform DCCs in all size classes. 
We can therefore argue that the presence of comparative advantage in Table 4. Univariate tests by size class and sector. 
