494 A. Mura et al. Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 FCCs is not driven by omitted variables reﬂecting ﬁrm-speciﬁc characteristics. 
These tests also show that these characteristics are signiﬁcant drivers of ﬁrm performance in Italy; namely, OWNER is not the only variable that enters the regression with a statistically signiﬁcant coefﬁcient. 
For instance, it appears that geographical location and size play inﬂuential roles in explaining the ROA level: regardless of ownership, companies located in the northern region outperform those in other regions as well as small and medium companies outperform large companies. 
These results are not surprising in the light of both the north2 south dualism that is peculiar to Italian history and the fact that small and medium companies have always represented the backbone of the Italian entrepreneurial system (Leonardi 1995, Cucculelli and Micucci 2008). 
Furthermore, the ROA improves as the capital ratio increases and when the ﬁxed over total assets and ﬁrm size declines. 
Notably, while the impact of EQUITY on ROA conﬁrms the ﬁnding in Langli and Saud agaran (2004) for a sample of Norway-based companies of a negative inﬂuence of leverage on ﬁrm performance, the sign of the relationship between FIXED and ROA in Italy is instead opposite. 
AGE appears positively related to proﬁtability only when ﬁrms have a great size (Q5) while the opposite holds for small and medium-sized ﬁrms. 
Next, to assess the robustness of our ﬁndings and to increase the degree of comparability between FCCs and DCCs, we have repeated the multivariate analysis separately for each sector. 
To ease the exposure and to save space, in Table 6 we present for each sector only the coefﬁcient of the variable OWNER, obtained from the regression analysis. 
8 The multivariate model estimated separately for the three sectors shows prevalently better performances in FCCs that in DCCs: the coefﬁcient of OWNER is positive and signiﬁcant at customary levels in 13 out of 15 sub-samples analysed under the multivariate setting. 
9 Finally, differently from previous related studies which normally analyse an earlier time period (Grubert et al. 1993, Crain and Stitts 1994, Oyelere and Emmanuel 1998, Langli and Saudagaran 2004), our analysis extends over a number of years where most European ﬁscal authorities have increasingly intensiﬁed their focus on transfer pricing compliance. 
Thus, our results might be driven by this growing focus on transfer pricing compliance that has led to reduce incentives for income-shifting practices. 
To verify the validity of this conjecture we have repeated the multivariate analysis separately for each year of the s ample period. 
The results of these tests, reported in Table 7, show that the signiﬁcant superior performance of FCCs as compared to DCCs does not appear related to a speciﬁc temporal pattern. 
We conclude, therefore, that it is unlikely that the peculiarity of our results is related to the increased scrutiny by regulators and ﬁscal authorities of international transfer pricing practice over the past decade. 
To summarise, the battery of multivariate tests discussed in this section reinforces the ﬁndings of the univariate analysis. 
First, in our sample FCCs outperform DCCs in terms of ROA. 
While this result is in contrast with the evidence found by several studies conducted in other institutional settings (USA, Germany, UK and Norway) to detect the presence of income-shifting policies in FCCs, it offers support for the internalisation theory and the related comparative advantage hypothesis. 
In sum, this result suggests that eith er tax minimisation in Italy is not the aim of FCCs or, more likely, if this is the case, the expected negative inﬂuence on proﬁtability is more than offset by positive effects stemming from comparative advantages. 
Second, in addition to the different levels of performance relating to ﬁrm ownership, it appears that several other factors are signiﬁcant determinants of ROA in Italy; namely, location, assets structure, investment policies and size are all key drivers of performances of companies based in Italy. 
These results imply that the comparison of the degree of proﬁtability between FCCs and DCCs by ﬁscal authorities needs to consider this full set of variables in the search for reliable comparables between the two groups of ﬁrms. 
