∗∗ Signiﬁcant at 5%. ∗∗∗ Signiﬁcant at 1%. 496 A. Mura et al. Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 5.3 Additional analyses In this section, we discuss several additional tests that we have conducted to corroborate the evidence reported in the previous sections. 
While the ratio between net operating proﬁt and total assets is one of the key performance measures usually employed to compare the degree of proﬁtability of FCCs and DCCs, it is generally suggested that additional performance measures should be used to assess the congruence of transfer pricing practices at the ﬁrm level (Przysuski and Lalapet 2005). 
In Table 8 we report the regression results when we employ two alternative proﬁt indicators which are constructed by using the proﬁt before taxes as a rough proxy of taxable income (Grubert et al. 1993, Klassen et al. 1993, Langli and Saudagaran 2004). 
Speciﬁcally, we estimate the regression model by asset size class using our measure of ‘Taxable Income’ scaled by total assets. 
In an effort to control for differences in debt policy we also use equity as an alternative scaling factor in the denominator. 
In the interest of brevity, we report only the results obtained when the models are estimated via median regression. 
Overall, these additional tests conﬁrm a higher proﬁtability in FCCs and support the view that the presence of a strong competitive advantage in these compa nies undermines the possibility to identify transfer pricing practices. 
One additional concern about our approach might be related to the presence of companies with low capital intensity for which both the classiﬁcation in size classes based on assets and the choice of the ROA might be inappropriate. 
Essentially, for these companies the value of sales represents a more adequate size variable and alternative proﬁt-margin indicators, such as the ROS or the ROC, are normally identiﬁed as acceptable performance measures to investigate transfer pricing abuses under the comparable proﬁts and transactional net margin methods (IRS,s482– 5; OECD 2010a, 2010b, par. 
2.58). 
We address this concern in Table 9 where we focus on the sub-sample of ﬁrms with low capital intensity measured by the ratio of total Table 7. Firm ownership and performance: analysis by year. 
