Accounting and Business Research 499 Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 assets and total sales. 
More speciﬁcally, ﬁrst we have classiﬁed the FCCs in quintiles based on the average value of capital intensity over the sample period; then, we have selected ﬁrms falling in the ﬁrst quintile and matched these ﬁrms with DCCs with a value of capital intensity falling in the range of the same quintile. 
The selected companies are then classiﬁed in ﬁve size classes based on sales in a similar manner as in the previous section. 
Finally, for each size class based on sales, Table 9 reports the regression results when the ratio between operating proﬁt and total sales or the ratio between operating proﬁt and total costs are employed as measures of performance. 
The results of these tests conﬁrm the ﬁnding observed in the previous sections. 
5.4 The interquartile range of the ROA distribution Our univariate and multivariate tests provide robust evidence of the presence of a signiﬁcant and positive difference in median performances between FCCs and DCCs in Italy and this is in line with the postulates of the internalisation theory. 
However, the comparability of the performances of a te sted company with those of unrelated independent companies to detect transfer pricing manipulations, as generally conducted by ﬁscal authorities in accordance with the transfer pricing guidelines established by the OECD (2010a, 2010b), may go beyond the analysis of the median values of a measure of performance. 
For instance, in the presence of a great number of observations it is suggested that the interquartile range or other percentiles will help in the search of comparables to justify the arm’s length range. 
In the context of the current analysis, the possibility to use additional analytical tools by ﬁscal authorities is particularly relevant as it might indicate that, in spite of the presence of a relevant comparative advantage in the median foreign ﬁrm, there is scope to activate transfer pricing enquires via the adoption of more reﬁned approaches. 
These enquires can then collect more information to uncover manipulations in transfer prices that otherwise would be ignored under the comparison of median performances. 
Table 10. Firm ownership and performance interquartile analysis; percentage values. 
Sample divided by size classes Q1 Q2 Q3 Q4 Q5 Panel A: full sample Below the 25 percentile 27.47 27.13 29.37 23.25 28.05 Inside the range 32.86 28.80 32.57 35.98 35.97 Above the 75 percentile 39.67 44.07 38.07 40.77 35.97 Panel B: manufacturing sector Below the 25 percentile 27.12 26.89 32.75 26.95 29.93 Inside the range 33.30 32.51 34.43 35.86 37.94 Above the 75 percentile 39.58 40.60 32.82 37.19 32.13 Panel C: commercial Below the 25 percentile 31.17 27.52 26.45 27.95 32.10 Inside the range 32.41 26.16 32.50 32.39 37.16 Above the 75 percentile 36.42 46.32 41.05 39.66 30.74 Panel D: services Below the 25 percentile 22.74 25.90 25.47 21.07 25.43 Inside the range 37.07 26.67 29.68 32.11 32.60 Above the 75 percentile 40.19 47.43 44.84 46.82 41.97 Notes: This table reports the interquartile range analysis according to the methodology discussed in Section 4.3. 
More precisely, the FCCs have been classiﬁed as falling within, below or above the interquartile range of the ROA distribution during the full sample period. 
While Panel A reports the results of this test for the full sample of FCCs classiﬁed in ﬁve size classes, Panels B, C and D show the results of the same analysis conducted separately for, respectively, manufacturing, commercial and service ﬁrms. 
500 A. Mura et al. Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 Table 10 extends, therefore, the empirical analysis to the investigation of the full distribution of the ROA for DCCs, initially for the full sample and then for each sector. 
Speciﬁcally, we identify, for the sub-samples based on size and on size and sector analysed in the univariate tests and in the regression analysis, the interquartile range of the ROA distribution. 
Next, we compute the percentage of foreign ﬁrms that fall inside and outside this range. 
These tests show unequivocally that more than 70% of FCCs would not be subject to any ﬁscal enquiry either because their comparative advantage is particularly pronounced or because they report proﬁtability values within a tolerable range. 
In other words, in spite of operating in a high-tax country, only a minor share of FCCs seem to manipulate transfer prices to such an extent as to attract the consideration of ﬁscal authorities. 
In general, this conclusion also holds when the analysis is conducted separately for each sector; namely, when we attempt to increase the degree of comparability between FCCs and DCCs. 
Overall, these results conﬁrm the hypothesis that there are signiﬁcant differences in performance between FCCs and independent DCCs operating in Italy and conﬁrm a potential room for an unimpeded use of transfer pricing manipulation. 
This is because ﬁscal authorities are not likely to set their sights on numerous FCCs, as they are unfairly unsuspected under the shield of a reassuring high proﬁtability due to comparative advantage. 
In this respect, the use of the analysis of the interquartile range as an assessment method does not seem effective even for FCCs where the comparative advantages do not fully materialise and the reported proﬁtability levels are unlikely to induce any ﬁscal enquiry. 
6. Conclusions Our ﬁndings contradict the traditional evidence in the international transfer pricing empirical literature (see for example Collins et al. 1997, Grubert 1997, Collins et al. 1998, Emmanuel and Oyelere 2002, Langli and Saudagaran 2004) by showing that FCCs outperform their Italian independent counterparts at a sta tistically signiﬁcant level. 
This result holds when alternative proﬁtlevel indicators and more precise comparators are incorpo rated within the analysis. 
Furthermore, the application of the interquartile range to detect acceptable arm’s length proﬁts highlights that a high proportion of FCCs either reports performance within the interquartile range of the ROA distribution or above. 
Unexpectedly, in a country with an extremely high taxation, the comparability method, even in its more reﬁned approach, suggests that transfer pricing manipulation is not a major issue. 
A possible explanation for our results can be related to the speciﬁcities of Italy in terms of level of taxation, foreign direct investment attractiveness and legal enforcement: the performance differential appears a plausible consequence of strong comparative advantages that FCCs operating in Italy may enjoy. 
Thus, the expectation of a similar proﬁtability between a given tested FCC and a set of comparable independent companies as a proof that transfer prices are set at arm’s length appears potentially fallacious. 
The presence of these comparative advantages might depend on a lower quality of DCCs management and a consequent lower business efﬁciency. 
Furthermore, the magnitude of this advantage in terms of performance differential might be inﬂated by a greater aggressiveness in tax avoidance by DCCs. 
In this respect, we speculate that especially small and medium-sized Italian ﬁrms, often individually or family owned, might be more ﬂexible and effective in exploiting a low level of tax enforcement and thus hiding their proﬁtability given the absence of strong outside shareholders (Desai et al. 2007). 
On the basis of our results, we argue that the capability of tax authorities to detect and police transfer price manipulation has to rely more heavily on judgement than apparently “hard” ﬁnancial data and this provides an explanation for the investigation of individual intra-group Accounting and Business Research 501 Downloaded by [Open University Library - ISRAEL] at 11:28 28 October 2013 transactions and activities. 
The exercise of judgement by ﬁscal agents becomes of paramount importance but, as Ernst & Young surveys (2011) have shown, the preferred methods for intangibles and intellectual property activities are the comparable proﬁts and transactional net margin methods. 
These are precisely the intra-group activities where comparative advantages come to the fore and where internalisation legitimises proﬁtability differentials. 
They are also activities where even inexact comparables may not exist or can be contested. 
The lack of focus on individual transactions or individual FCCs represents a limitation of this study. 
In addition, the analysis ignores the total tax regime operating in Italy and does not attempt to recognise the importance of intra-group transactions involving DCCs with differing degrees of international involvement. 
Nevertheless, we show that a careful analysis of comparables using the reﬁned indirect method and the OEC D-recommended method gives rise to ambiguous interpretations. 
The reliability of the tests of comparability therefore seems a reasonable starting point for debate on whether the arm’s length principle should remain the cornerstone of ﬁscal regulation. 
The recent proposal of the European Commission to introduce the Common Consolidated Corporate Tax Base to tax multinational enterprises operating in Europe may, arguably, bypass all potential disputes over internal transfer prices. 
An alternative view is that the comparables problem is then replaced by a formula apportionment problem that is equally intractable. 
Nonetheless, in their indifference towards detailed disclosure of international transfer pricing policies, accounting standard setters appear surprisingly convergent across countries. 
