This paper has also greatly beneﬁtted from the wise comments of Pauline Weetman and Vivien Beattie (editors) as well as from two challenging anonymous referees. 
Notes 1. The peculiarities of Italy emerge when this country is compared with the other countries analysed in prior international transfer pricing empirical studies. 
In particular, the USA, the UK, Germany and Norway rank, respectively, 69, 77, 74 and 59 on the extent and effect of tax and, respectively, 103, 67, 103 and 82 in terms of total tax rate. 
In terms of “Business impact of rules on FDI”, the same countries are ranked as 64, 13, 72 and 79. 2. Traditionally transaction-based methods such as full cost plus, resale price and comparable uncontrolled price have been recommended to detect international transfer pricing manipulation. 
They examine the prices of speciﬁc transactions wherever possible using comparable prices between unassociated enterprises. 
It has been clearly demonstrated that transaction-based comparables are of questionable reliability and are not necessarily consistent with transaction cost economics (Eden 1998, Emmanuel and Cools 2007). 
That is, asset, location, human speciﬁcity and other forms that comprise multinational enterprise comparative advantage are not capable of accurate measurement or easily observed even when similar transactions are the focus of analysis. 
These concerns are emphasised when proﬁtbased methods of transfer pricing are applied. 
3. Similarly, under the US regulations, reliability depends on the comparability of the controlled and unrelated party transactions or activities, the completeness and accuracy of the data, and the reliability of the assumptions made (IRS,s482 F94, 119). 
For proﬁt-based methods, the “arm’s length” principle is amended to compare the results of subsidiary activities for consistency with the results that uncontrolled taxpayers would obtain. 
When material differences exist, adjustment can be made, but this will depend on the completeness and accuracy of the data supplied by the taxpayer, the multinational enterprise. 
The burden of proof is, therefore, on the multinational enterprise to demonstrate reliability in order that comparables are acceptable and that compliance with the “arm’s length” principle can be shown. 
